<br>
To avoid exploiting this spell, a pet cannot be summoned to you if he exists currently on a hate list.  We receive the failure message: “Your pet is the focus of someone’s attention.”  To an extent, this works great and is a good measure to keep from accidentally pulling and helps avoid exploiting.<br>
<br>
 Unfortunately, this message may not be true at all.  We can often times be “tanking” the mob who’s attention our pet supposedly has our focus.  Many times I’ve seen melees tanking and a whole group properly surrounding the mob and killing it, meanwhile my pet that decided to choose a poor route to attack the mob, has taunted and then gotten himself lost, or my pet is limited by some specific geographical boundary and thus cannot path across it.  Once the battle has ended, I can them summon my pet to me.  <br>
<br>
As mages we give a tremendous amount of power to have our pets.  We lose a great deal of defensive capabilities.  Other than gate, our *only* defense is our pets and nukes (offense.)  If our pet is not available to us, we are truly defenseless.  Against monsters that a person from level 39 up will face, a mage cannot tank for long.  In the 50s, mobs will tear a mage down in no time. <br>
<br>
The Problem: A pet can taunt a mob outside of certain geometric limits.  I’m not quite sure HOW pet taunting is limited, but it certainly isn’t limited to any great extent.  When a pet Taunt’s, if the mob has received no other agro, he will FIRST attack the mage.  If the pet is close enough to intercept, he will do so.  Unfortunately, this taunt adds the pet to the monster’s hate list.  This then excludes the option of the pet being summoned to us.<br>
<br>
These problems aren’t rare at all.  Here are some case examples:<br>
<br>
Charasis / Howling Stones: a mage has his/her pet summoned up at zone in.  He/she jumps down to begin killing the ravagers and other mobs in hopes of getting a key to begin fighting through the zone.  Unfortunately, upon impacting the ground, the mage is instantly aggro’d.  Our pet, in hopes of assisting us, taunts the mob.  Once the mob has been taunted, we cannot summon our pet to us, until that mob has died.<br>
<br>
Mines to Acrylia in Grimling Forest:  The pathing here is terrible, but using summon companion we can manage.  Unfortunately on one quick kill, I sent my pet in.  He taunted the mob and then decided instead of running toward the mob, he would run out of the mine system entirely.  Unfortunately, there was no way to summon my pet to me, even though the group had completely engaged the mob.  “Your pet is the focus of someone’s attention.”<br>
<br>
Nurga: This zone is constructed entirely as a mining facility.  The nature and idea of the zone is rather interesting.  Unfortunately, there are multiple places were a person, who wants to continue fighting through the mine, must jump down.  Our pets have no way of pathing down to us.  If we get agro from the mobs immediately below us, our pet will taunt to assist us, and then get stuck in pathing (as there is no logical pathway down to us).  We then have to tank the mob, gate, or die.<br>
<br>
In many other zones there exist certain geometric boundaries, or logical boundaries from pathing.  Unfortunately, these boundaries affect our ability of our pet to join us into battle, but however, do not affect our pet’s ability to taunt.  These geometric and logical boundaries are therefore, particularly lethal, as a mage has no ability to defend himself other than the use of gate and nukes.  Such boundaries put a mage at a greatly increased risk, as we have no way to deal with traps, cliffs, and pits effectively.<br>
<br>
Summon companion also does not properly work in air.  So we cannot levitate over these geometric boundaries in hopes of summoning our pet and “dropping” him into the room we wish.  Unfortunately our pet will kill himself.<br>
<br>
Solutions - There are many different solutions to the problem and actually there may be multiple different problems (pathing, zone geometry). <br>
<br>
#1 – Fix Summon Companion to work as the message indicates and allow us to summon our pet IF he is not under attack. (Difficult to code, perhaps a challenging fix, but perhaps the most effective.)<br>
<br>
#2 – Repair pathing in those zones were this is a problem.  (Countless numbers of zones have certain geographic anomalies which will create these scenarios, and therefore making this solution far from realistic).<br>
<br>
#3 – Force the mage to disable taunting at all times when traversing zones.  (Unfortuantely, by disabling the taunt FEATURE of our pet, we put ourselves at a greater risk of over nuking the agro generated from our pet.  Unfortunately, this isn’t always acceptable).<br>
<br>
#4 – Give the pet restrictions (or repair them) on his taunting ability.<br>
    There are two ways to do this effectively:<br>
<br>
1 – Limit the pet’s taunting range to his melee range on X, Y, and Z Axis’s (this would require a deep coded fix which Verant would probably shy away from and isn’t a very realistic fix).<br>
<br>
2 – Only allow the pet to taunt AFTER he has engaged in melee against that mob (simple Boolean variable check.  Even a simple hasMeleed variable would work VERY well over the complete lack of checks.  It would be a marked improvement even if there are multiple mobs; there would be little side effect.  ALSO, implementation of this solution would require minor coding [approximately 5 minutes by my guess].  A simple Boolean variable check would require the most minimal computing resources and on a large scale would not add any significant load what-so-ever. – There would be side effects to this fix however.  Example: A mage kiting would not have the benefit of pet taunting if he could not engage in melee against the mob)<br>
<br>
So there you have it: The Problem, The Examples, The Explanation, and The Solution.  Any thoughts or comments would be appreciated =).  Please correct me if I'm made any errors.<br>
